                <head>589. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On October 13, <persName corresp="#p_WJJ1">James J. Wadsworth</persName>,
                    Representative to the United Nations, transmitted to <gloss target="#t_UN1">U.
                        N.</gloss> Secretary-General Dag Hammarskjöld a paper entitled, “Facts
                    Concerning Relations Between Cuba and the United States: A Reply to Allegations
                    Made in the United Nations Against the United States by Prime Minister <persName
                        corresp="#p_CRF1">Fidel Castro</persName> of Cuba.” <persName
                        corresp="#p_WJJ1">Wadsworth</persName> asked that the paper be circulated to
                    all members of the United Nations for their information. The text of the paper,
                    along with <persName corresp="#p_WJJ1">Wadsworth</persName>’s letter of
                    transmittal, October 12, is printed in Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                        >Bulletin</hi>, October 31, 1960, pages 690–701.</p>
                <p>In telegram 992 from <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>, October 13, <persName
                        corresp="#p_WJJ1">Wadsworth</persName> reported that he had “reluctantly”
                    transmitted the document to the Secretary-General. <persName corresp="#p_WJJ1"
                        >Wadsworth</persName> expressed his belief that the paper was “totally
                    unsuited” to the purpose for which it was needed, since it was much <pb
                        facs="1116" n="1084" xml:id="pg_1084"/> too long and gave too much attention
                    to a rehearsal of economic history and arguments unresponsive to <persName
                        corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>’s allegations that were mainly
                    political. (Department of State, Central Files, 611.37/10–1360)</p>
            </div>
